{{lead too short|date=November 2010}} {{primarysources|date=November 2010}} '''GnomeVFS''' is short for [[GNOME]] Virtual File System. It provides an [[Abstraction (computer science)|abstraction layer]] for the reading, writing and execution of files. It was primarily used by the [[Nautilus file manager]] and other [[List of GNOME applications|GNOME applications]] before GNOME 2.22.
A cause of confusion is the fact that the [[file system]] abstraction used by the [[Linux kernel]] is also called the [[virtual file system]] (VFS) layer. This is however at a lower level.
A replacement<ref>[http://mail.gnome.org/archives/gtk-devel-list/2006-September/msg00072.html GnomeVFS shortcomings]</ref> called [[GVFS]]<ref>[http://live.gnome.org/GioToDo Gio TODO]</ref> is currently in development which also allows partitions to be mounted through [[Filesystem in Userspace|FUSE]].<ref>[http://mail.gnome.org/archives/gtk-devel-list/2007-February/msg00062.html gvfs status report, Alexander Larsson, mail.gnome.org, February 15, 2007]</ref>
{{As of|2008|4}}, the GNOME project has declared GnomeVFS [[deprecation|deprecated]] in favour of [[GVFS]] and [[GIO (GNOME)|GIO]], requesting that developers not use it in new applications.<ref>GNOME 2.22 Release Notes, [http://library.gnome.org/misc/release-notes/2.22/#sect:gvfs-gio 6.1: GVFS and GIO]</ref>
